{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585291"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:08:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:08:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14951"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14951"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.21,0.5,0,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7639"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14951"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97413"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18685"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring acute inflammation, increased vascular permeability occurs through several mechanisms. One important mechanism is leukocyte-dependent vascular injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following blood vessels is most affected by leukocyte-dependent injury during acute inflammation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Venules","Arterioles","Capillaries","Veins","Arteries"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring acute inflammation, \u003Cstrong\u003Evenules\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary site of leukocyte-dependent vascular injury. This occurs because post-capillary venules have the optimal conditions for leukocyte adhesion and migration through the endothelium. The slow blood flow in venules allows for effective leukocyte-endothelial interactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterioles\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Earteries\u003C/strong\u003E have blood flow that is too rapid for significant leukocyte adhesion. \u003Cstrong\u003ECapillaries\u003C/strong\u003E have lumens that are too narrow for effective leukocyte migration. \u003Cstrong\u003EVeins\u003C/strong\u003E are too large and have flow characteristics that do not support optimal leukocyte-endothelial interactions. The process of leukocyte migration involves rolling, adhesion, and transmigration, which requires specific conditions found primarily in post-capillary venules.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-capillary venules are the primary site of leukocyte adhesion and migration during acute inflammation","Slow blood flow in venules allows optimal conditions for leukocyte-endothelial interactions","Other blood vessels are less suitable for leukocyte migration due to their size or blood flow characteristics"],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Punchard NA, Whelan CJ, Adcock I. The Journal of Inflammation. J Inflamm (Lond). 2004 Sep 27;1(1):1. doi: 10.1186/1476-9255-1-1. PMID: 15813979; PMCID: PMC1074343","Margraf A, Lowell CA, Zarbock A. Neutrophils in acute inflammation: current concepts and translational implications. Blood. 2022 Apr 7;139(14):2130-2144. doi: 10.1182/blood.2021012295. PMID: 34624098; PMCID: PMC9728535","Zanoli L, Briet M, Empana JP, Cunha PG, M\u00e4ki-Pet\u00e4j\u00e4 KM, Protogerou AD, Tedgui A, Touyz RM, Schiffrin EL, Spronck B, Bouchard P, Vlachopoulos C, Bruno RM, Boutouyrie P; Association for Research into Arterial Structure, Physiology (ARTERY) Society, the European Society of Hypertension (ESH) Working Group on Vascular Structure and Function, and the European Network for Noninvasive Investigation of Large Arteries. Vascular consequences of inflammation: a position statement from the ESH Working Group on Vascular Structure and Function and the ARTERY Society. J Hypertens. 2020 Sep;38(9):1682-1698. doi: 10.1097/HJH.0000000000002508. PMID: 32649623; PMCID: PMC7610698."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14951"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T16:27:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T16:27:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7639"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115410"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/